As shown in 
, Compound 1 shows a 3D [Ag7(3-pttz)4]3+ host framework with larger channels. The discrete PMo12 clusters as templates are cemented into the channels. The host [Ag7(3-pttz)4]3+ MOF is divided into two moieties. One is a 2D layer formed by Ag3 ions and tetra-nuclear [Ag4(3-pttz)3] subunits, in which [Ag4(3-pttz)3] is constructed from three types of 3-pttz ligands, Ag4, Ag5, Ag6 and Ag7 ions (a). The adjacent tetra-nuclear subunits are fused together by Ag7–N8, Ag7–N13 and Ag6–N12 bonds in a hand by hand mode, generating an infinite organic–inorganic chain (A-type) along b axis (b). These parallel chains are further connected together by Ag3 ions and Ag5-N6 bond leading to a stair-like 2D MOF (c). The other moiety is the infinite [Ag2(3-pttz)] chains (B-type) constructed by Ag1, Ag2 and one 3-pttz ligand (d). The [Ag2(3-pttz)] chains connect adjacent layers via Ag2–N16, Ag6–N2 and Ag5–N3 bonds to form open 3D metal–organic host framework with the larger pores (ca. 9.6×13.1Å), as shown in e. The guest PMo12 clusters as templates occupy the large channels. From the topological view, if PMo12 are considered as three-connected nodes, Ag3 ions as three-connected nodes, A-type chains subunits as eight-connected nodes and B-type chains subunits as six-connected nodes, the interconnection of alternating two subunits, Ag3 and PMo12 results in an infinite 3D (3,3,6,8)-connected 4-nodal net (
) with the point symbol {4.52}{42.5}{45.52.67.7}{413.53.611.7}, which represents a new topology analyzed by the topos 4.0 program.
